LAGOS – Following the previous day’s loss, the Nigerian Stock Exchange (NSE) mar­ket posted a positive performance on Tuesday, gaining 0.17 per cent to settle at 40,465.15 points. The positive performance was driven by appreciation in Zenith Bank (+2.0%), United Bank for Africa (+2.4%) and International Breweries (+2.5%). As a result, the year-to-date (YTD) return improved to 0.5 per cent while market capitalisation advanced by N36.1 billion to settle at N21.2 trillion. ABUJA DOCTOR REVEALS HOW MOST NIGERIA MEN ARE NOW OVERCOMING TERRIBLE BEDROOM PERFORMANCE DUE TO THIS BRILLIANT DISCOVERY. DON'T BE A VICTIM! Activity level decreased as volume and value traded fell 46.4 per cent and 57.3 per cent to 249.5 million units and N2.2 billion respectively. The most traded stocks by volume were Access Bank with 21.9 million units, Mansard Insurance with 13.3 mil­lion units and United Bank for Africa with 13.2 million units while Guaranty Trust Bank at N342.0 million, Zenith Bank at N310.4 million and Stanbic IBTC at N306.2 million topped by value. Southern, Middle Belt Forum Appoints Nwodo As National Coordinator COVID-19 Investigations: WHO Blasts China For Blocking Team From Entering Country Performance across sectors was bullish as four of six indices covered gained save the AFR-ICT and Indus­trial Goods indices which closed flat. The Insurance and Oil & Gas indi­ces topped the gainers, rising 3.0 per cent and 0.1 per cent respectively due to buying interest in Mansard Insurance (+7.8%), NEM Insurance (+9.7%) and Oando (+2.1%). Lastly, the banking and consum­er goods indices gained 0.8 per cent and 0.3 per cent respectively, buoyed by price appreciation in Zenith Bank (+2.0%), United Bank for Africa (+2.4%) and International Breweries (+2.5%). Investor sentiment as measured by market breadth (advance/decline ratio) strengthened to 1.4x from the 0.4x recorded previously as 22 stocks advanced against 16 decliners. NEM Insurance (+9.7%), BOC Gas­es (+9.5%) and Linkage Assurance (+9.3%) were the best-performing tickers while Sovereign Insurance (-8.3%), Eterna Oil (-8.2%) and Deap Capital (-8.0%) were the losers.